{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36290,"record_hash":"sha256:880c72c93380ff1d5c07a356562f360f7d14d7027f567f7c084494fa7ccd52e4","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:51:50.448Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Delete File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/session-association-risks.md\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/session-association-strategy.md\n+# Session Association Strategy\n+\n+This note explores how captured agent sessions could be connected to branches,\n+changes, commits, or pull requests. It is not an implementation plan. Its job is\n+to compare paths, keep the brittle parts visible, and identify pragmatic\n+shortcuts that support the two future use cases:\n+\n+- session handoff across machines or agents\n+- review sharing through a GitButler timeline of relevant agent sessions\n+\n+## What We Want\n+\n+The durable object is still the project-scoped agent session:\n+\n+```text\n+project\n+  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n+```\n+\n+Future review or branch objects should reference those sessions:\n+\n+```text\n+<branch/change/commit/pr target>\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+The relationship should mean \"this session is relevant to this target\", not\n+\"this session uniquely generated this target\". That wording matters because the\n+real workflow is many-to-many:\n+\n+- one session can contribute to several branches or pull requests\n+- one branch or pull request can involve several sessions\n+- a session can be useful context even before any code exists\n+- a session can contain useful discussion even if no generated code is kept\n+\n+## Key Constraint\n+\n+Capture-time association is weak evidence. The current branch may be wrong, a\n+GitButler worktree can contain several active branches, and the user may later\n+split generated edits across destinations. Capture should continue to write\n+project-scoped sessions and avoid inferred ownership.\n+\n+Commit, amend, and PR moments have better evidence, but they are still not\n+perfect. Users can wait hours before committing, mix manual edits with generated\n+code, squash generated work into older manual commits, or use plain Git outside\n+GitButler.\n+\n+The safest design line is:\n+\n+```text\n+inference may suggest; only explicit or high-confidence confirmation should persist\n+```\n+\n+False positives are worse than missed links because they can mislead reviewers\n+about how code was produced.\n+\n+## Approach Options\n+\n+| Approach | Shape | Strengths | Weaknesses | Fit |\n+| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n+| Capture-time inference | Hook capture writes a branch/change/session link from current workspace state. | Fully automatic. Very small UI burden. | Current branch is often the wrong evidence. Bad for multi-branch worktrees and delayed commits. | Avoid. |\n+| Explicit attach | User or CLI attaches a session to a target. | Smallest implementation. Trustworthy. Matches current data model. | Users can forget. Links may be coarse. | Good first step. |\n+| Suggest-and-confirm at commit/amend | Commit UI ranks recent sessions and asks the user to attach selected ones. | Uses real change evidence while controlling false positives. | Adds UI/workflow. Ranking can still be wrong. | Strong next step. |\n+| PR/review prep picker | PR or review UI lets the user choose related sessions before sharing. | Directly supports review sharing. Easy post-hoc correction. Avoids mutation lifecycle hooks. | Coarser than change-level provenance. Less useful before a PR exists. | Very attractive shortcut. |\n+| Change-id primary links | Confirmed sessions attach to durable GitButler change ids. Branch/PR views union sessions from reachable changes. | Best GitButler-native code anchor. Survives many rewrites better than commit SHA. | Squash, uncommit/recommit, synthetic change ids, and external Git still need care. | Good later, once review UI needs code-level links. |\n+| Commit SHA links plus propagation | Attach to exact commits and copy links through rewrites. | Exact for a specific revision. | High lifecycle footprint. Rebase/squash/amend/move/undo all need custom behavior. | Avoid early. |\n+| Evidence/recompute | Store or derive evidence from time, files, tool calls, and patch similarity; compute links later. | Can power useful suggestions without mutating metadata. | Privacy, performance, explainability, and false-positive risk. | Use for suggestions only, not durable truth. |\n+| Active session pin | User marks a session as \"for this work\"; later commit/PR UI preselects it. | Reduces detective work. Helps handoff before code exists. | Can go stale. Needs obvious clear/expiry behavior. | Possible UX shortcut. |\n+\n+## Most Promising Path\n+\n+Use a layered, explicit-first model:\n+\n+1. Keep capture project-scoped.\n+2. Let users explicitly attach sessions to targets.\n+3. Use inference only to rank suggestions.\n+4. Confirm before writing durable relationships.\n+5. Prefer change ids over branches or commit SHAs when code-level association is\n+   needed.\n+6. Let branch and PR views derive their related sessions by unioning lower-level\n+   relationships.\n+\n+This gives a useful product path without immediately paying the full lifecycle\n+cost. The first useful review-sharing flow could be a PR or review prep picker:\n+show recent sessions with transcript previews, let the user choose which ones are\n+relevant, then write relationship sets. That supports the web timeline use case\n+without needing to hook squash, move, undo, rebase, and uncommit first.\n+\n+For handoff, the shortcut is different: a user can choose a project session\n+directly from the session index, or later pin/attach an active session to the\n+work they intend to continue. Handoff does not require proving which branch the\n+session eventually affected.\n+\n+## Whole Session Or Portion Of Session\n+\n+Associating an entire session is pragmatic and simple. It also works naturally\n+with the current project-scoped transcript model.\n+\n+The downside is noise:\n+\n+- a multi-day session may include unrelated work\n+- early planning may apply to one branch while later tool use applies to another\n+- a reviewer may only need a small window of the transcript\n+\n+Persisting transcript slices is more precise in theory, but brittle in practice.\n+The slice can become misleading after manual edits, squashes, moves, or later\n+conversation. A better early direction is to store the session relationship and\n+let future readers derive likely relevant windows from timestamps, files, tool\n+mentions, and user selection.\n+\n+## Mutation Lifecycle Risks\n+\n+Once relationships exist, they can drift when code is reshaped.\n+\n+Operations that can break or blur the relationship:\n+\n+- **Amend:** the same change may need to preserve old session links and add a\n+  new one if the amendment came from a later session.\n+- **Uncommit and recommit:** relationships can be orphaned, duplicated, or\n+  attached to the wrong new object if change identity is not preserved.\n+- **Split or move hunks:** one original association may need to be copied,\n+  divided, or dropped across multiple destinations.\n+- **Squash:** source session links should probably be unioned into the\n+  destination. Otherwise a large AI-generated change squashed into a small\n+  manual change can lose provenance if the destination change id wins.\n+- **Reorder or rebase:** commit ids change. Links attached only to commit ids\n+  will be fragile; durable change ids are a better anchor when available.\n+- **Branch rename, delete, or recreate:** branch-level links are convenient for\n+  views but weak as the primary durable relationship.\n+- **Undo and redo:** replayed operations can accidentally replay stale metadata\n+  changes or forget them entirely.\n+- **Plain Git operations outside GitButler:** commits, rebases, and squashes can\n+  bypass GitButler's association logic.\n+\n+The implementation risk is footprint. If every operation needs custom metadata\n+edge handling, one missed path creates silent provenance drift.\n+\n+## Change IDs As Anchors\n+\n+GitButler change ids look like the best future code-level anchor, but they are\n+not magic.\n+\n+They are better than commit SHAs because GitButler can preserve them through many\n+rewrites. They are better than branches because branches are labels over moving\n+sets of changes. They also match the review UI concept of a patch/change.\n+\n+Risks to keep explicit:\n+\n+- synthetic change ids derived from commit ids are not durable across rewrites\n+- two different pieces of content can share a change id over time\n+- squash may keep one surviving change id and drop the others\n+- uncommit/recommit can break the relationship unless the user confirms it again\n+- plain Git operations can bypass GitButler's ability to maintain links\n+\n+If automatic propagation becomes necessary, prefer one centralized association\n+operation over scattered set mutations across every commit lifecycle path.\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Which signals are strong enough to preselect a suggested session?\n+- Should the commit UI ask the user to confirm suggested sessions?\n+- Should PR/review publishing include a required or optional session picker?\n+- Should GitButler track an explicit \"active agent session\" during a workspace\n+  session?\n+- How should non-GitButler Git operations be represented, if at all?\n+- Should relationships be stored permanently, recomputed from evidence, or both?\n+- How much uncertainty should be shown to reviewers?\n+- What is the smallest centralized API that can keep association updates out of\n+  every individual mutation path?\n+\n+## Cautious Direction\n+\n+Do not infer association at capture time.\n+\n+Start with explicit relationships and suggestion-assisted confirmation. The\n+first high-value shortcut is likely a PR/review prep picker because it directly\n+supports review sharing without requiring lifecycle propagation. The next step,\n+if code-level precision is needed, is confirmed change-id association with\n+derived branch/PR views.\n+\n+Keep stored links coarse: \"these sessions are relevant\". Let readers derive\n+transcript windows later.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/future-use-cases.md\n@@\n-See [Session Association Risks](session-association-risks.md) for the brittle\n-parts of inferring and maintaining those relationships.\n+See [Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) for possible\n+paths and the brittle parts of inferring and maintaining those relationships.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/gitmeta-data-model.md\n@@\n-See [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for access patterns and product\n-motivation, and [Session Association Risks](session-association-risks.md) for\n-why inferred relationships should stay cautious.\n+See [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for access patterns and product\n+motivation, and [Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md)\n+for why inferred relationships should stay cautious.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n - [GitMeta Data Model](gitmeta-data-model.md)\n - [Agentlog Sync Lifecycle](agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md)\n - [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md)\n+- [Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md)\n - [Capture Workflow](capture-workflow.md)\n - [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md)\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:51:50.448Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"